FRIDA: Free-Rider Detection using Privacy Attacks

Pol G. Recasens Barcelona Supercomputing Center
pol.garcia@bsc.es    Ádám Horváth Budapest Univ. of Tech. and Eco.
adi.horvath1214@gmail.com    Alberto Gutierrez-Torre {@IEEEauthorhalign} Jordi Torres Barcelona Supercomputing Center
alberto.gutierrez@bsc.es Barcelona Supercomputing Center
Universitat Politecnica de Catalunya
jordi.torres@bsc.es    Josep Ll.Berral Universitat Politecnica de Catalunya
Barcelona Supercomputing Center
josep.ll.berral@upc.edu    Balázs Pejó CrySyS Lab, Budapest Univ.
pejo@crysys.hu
Abstract

Federated learning is increasingly popular as it enables multiple parties with limited datasets and resources to train a high-performing machine learning model collaboratively. However, similarly to other collaborative systems, federated learning is vulnerable to free-riders – participants who do not contribute to the training but still benefit from the shared model. Free-riders not only compromise the integrity of the learning process but also slow down the convergence of the global model, resulting in increased costs for the honest participants.
To address this challenge, we propose FRIDA: free-rider detection using privacy attacks, a framework that leverages inference attacks to detect free-riders. Unlike traditional methods that only capture the implicit effects of free-riding, FRIDA directly infers details of the underlying training datasets, revealing characteristics that indicate free-rider behaviour. Through extensive experiments, we demonstrate that membership and property inference attacks are effective for this purpose. Our evaluation shows that FRIDA outperforms state-of-the-art methods, especially in non-IID settings.

Index Terms:
Federated Learning; Free-Riding; Inference Attack; Privacy; Security

I Introduction

Our daily lives are inevitably intertwined with computers as we use them extensively for leisure and work. This enabled companies to cheaply collect vast amounts of data about their users, which in turn empowered the emergence of machine learning (ML) [55]. Nevertheless, decisions based on single datasets may lead to suboptimal or biased results, which led to the evolution of federated learning (FL) [31], where multiple data holders could jointly train a single machine learning model to realize enhanced prediction power.

Despite its potential, FL faces several challenges related to data distribution, contribution score computation, security, and privacy [20]. For instance, the participants’ datasets might be non-homogeneous, making a weighted average aggregation method (FedAvg [31]) less effective. Although other aggregation techniques like FedProx [26] and Scaffold [21] have been proposed to address this issue, it remains an open challenge.

An orthogonal problem to data distribution is contribution evaluation (CE) [18], which consists on determining the value of the participants. Although the final model in FL is shared, externalities can still arise (e.g., by selling the final model), making the distributions of such gains a complex issue. Without an appropiate reward allocation scheme, the federation could even collapse. The holy grail of contribution scoring is the Shapley Value [49, 38], which is exponentially hard to compute. Hence, several approximations have been developed, such as Data Shapley [12] and Distributional Shapley [11].

Concerning the security aspect, risks include poisoning [42] and backdoor attacks [2], which inject unintended malicious behaviour into the models and undermine their reliability. To address these risks, techniques such as randomized smoothing [5] and certified robustness [23]) for robust training, as well as Byzantine Fault Tolerant (BFT) aggregation schemes such as KRUM [3], FoolsGold [9] and Bulyan [14]), have been proposed to protect the model’s reliability.

Regarding privacy risks, trained models could leak sensitive information about the datasets through techniques such as membership inference attacks (MIA) [40], property inference attacks (PIA) [34], and reconstruction attacks (Rec) [56]. Several defense techniques ara available, including secure aggregation (SA) [4] and differential privacy (DP) [36]. The former is a secure multiparty computation technique (SMPC) [6] that hides individual gradients during aggregation, while the latter uses noise to conceal the influence of any single datapoint.

These directions are usually tackled in isolation, yet they significantly influence one another. For instance, many BFT aggregation techniques and CE mechanisms are incompatible with privacy-protection methods like SA, as SA conceals individual gradients, which form the basis of many BFT and CE schemes. Additionally, there is a tension between BFT and CE when it comes to data distribution: detecting attackers or ordering honest participants becomes much more challenging with heterogeneous datasets. It is even more difficult to detect or score free-riders, as their impact is minimal compared to that of harmful malicious and harmless honest clients.

Consequently, the issue of free-riding (FR) [15, 22] lies at the intersection of CE and BFT. In FL, free-riders [27, 8, 57] are non-malicious selfish clients who disguise their lack of contribution during training to benefit from the global model. They do not intend to cause harm or alter the learning objective intentionally. However, they implicitly delay the model’s convergence (as shown in Fig. 1) and compromise fairness, which results in more resources (time and computation) invested by the honest participants.

Contribution

In this interdisciplinary paper, we propose various solutions for the less-studied security problem of free-riding in FL using privacy attacks. We have developed four detection mechanisms to identify clients who do not contribute to the model’s training. Our mechanisms rely on inferred information about the client’s underlying datasets. The methods include loss-based and cosine-based (which rely on membership inference), as well as consistency-based and diversity-based approaches (which rely on property inference). Our contributions are detailed below.

  • •

    We propose four methods for utilizing privacy attacks (MIA & PIA) to detect FR clients: our approaches addresses the core issue directly — the lack of training — rather than relying on secondary effects of the underlying FR strategy.

  • •

    We establish a new connection between FL security and privacy by applying privacy attacks (MIA and PIA) to address a security problem (FR client detection).

We validate our approach through extensive experiments with multiple datasets, various model architectures and the two main FR strategies. Also, we compare our solutions to feature-based methods that capture the indirect effects of free-riding, and demonstrate that our methods outperform these approaches across numerous settings.

Organization

In Section II, we review the related literature and introduce the preliminaries utilized in this work. In Section III, we detail how privacy attacks can be adapted to detect free-riders. In Section IV, we describe the experimental setup and present the corresponding results. Finally, in Section V, we conclude our work, highlight its limitations, and propose several future directions.

II Background & Related Works

In this section, besides elaborating on the related works, we iterate through the core techniques used in the paper, such as misbehaviour detection and various privacy attacks.

II-A Misbehaviour Detection

Within FL, there are two schools of thought on how malicious behaviour is handled: mitigation and detection. Mitigation modifies the aggregation technique [13], while detection modifies the client sampling [44]. Both approaches aim to reduce the impact of malicious/suspicious clients within the federation. Mitigation mechanisms typically use robust statistics, such as the median [37], or compare the local updates either to each other or to a ground truth/baseline, such as the global model or a reference model. These comparisons generally rely on distance metrics such as Euclidean distance [3] or Cosine similarity [9].

Regarding detection, most techniques classify clients as honest or malicious by assigning various scores to participants. These scores are then used with relative or absolute thresholds to remove underperforming clients from the collaboration.

II-A1 Contribution Evaluation

The flagship technique is the Shapley-value (SV) [49], originating from cooperative game theory. It is the only scheme proven to satisfy four desired axioms: efficiency, symmetry, linearity, and null player. As a result, it has been widely used in ML for tasks such as feature selection, data valuation, and client scoring [38].

As computing the exact SV is computationally infeasible in many real-world scenarios, several model-agnostic approximations have been proposed [12, 11]. Although the SV is theoretically sound, it is unclear to what extent these approximations satisfy the four fairness principles outlined above. From the perspective of FR detection, the null player axiom is fundamental as it ensures that players who contribute nothing are assigned a score of zero. However, to the best of our knowledge, the scientific literature has exclusively focused on low scores (to remove harmful clients) or high scores (to boost performance) while disregarding FR [19].

II-A2 Free-riding

The authors in [8] provided a theoretical framework that formalized the FR attack and showed that the global model with FR still converges to the optimum albeit at a slower convergence rate. Within FR clients, we distinguish between two groups, called anonymous and selfish [47]. Clients within the former group do not have computational power or data, while clients in the latter have these resources but choose not to use them. The primary cause for anonymous FR is a lack of resources, whereas selfish FR mainly occurs due to economic incentives, such as minimizing computational costs or avoiding privacy leakage (which can lead to a loss of competitiveness). We focus on anonymous FR (simply called FR in the rest of the paper), primarily because FL is frequently used in critical scenarios involving sensitive data where clients lack access to public data. FR mainly relies on adding Gaussian perturbations to the global parameters or to the model updates, aiming to blend with the stochastic behaviour of the training process (e.g., SGD).

Several FR strategies have been proposed  [27, 57, 8]. The authors in [27] introduced the random weights attack, where the gradient update is generated by randomly sampling each parameter uniformly. They also proposed the advanced delta weights attack, which construct the gradient update by adding noise to the aggregated gradient of the previous round. A similar attack was presented in [57], where geometrical properties in IID scenarios are used to scale the update and improve stealth. The authors in [8] introduced the disguised free-rider, where noise is added to the previous global model (instead of the gradient) to mimic the SGD noise of honest clients. In this paper, we build on [27, 8], denoting them as ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and ℱFsuperscriptℱ𝐹\mathcal{F}^{F}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, respectively. More details will follow in Sec. III and the Appendix.

II-A3 Free-rider Detection

Compared to misbehaviour detection, the literature on FR is relatively sparse, with a primary focus on outlier detection. The authors in [27] proposed the Deep Autoencoding Gaussian Mixture Model (DAGMM) as a defence mechanism against FR, which has been further improved in subsequent works  [17, 45]. While this approach enhances the performance of outlier detection methods, it comes with high computational cost.

FR has also been addressed through incentive mechanisms [53], which promote collaborative fairness using a model-as-a-reward approach. In this framework, clients who make higher contributions receive more advanced models compared to those with lower or no contributions [29, 51, 46]. While the authors of [46] explored selfish FR that have access to both public and private data, most of these frameworks primarily focus on naive anonymous FR strategies based on uploading random noise.

II-A4 Privacy Considerations

Privacy-Preserving Federated Learning (PPFL) complicates the detection of malicious clients, as well as scoring the honest ones, due to the encryption of their gradient updates. Most schemes utilize advanced cryptographic primitives such as Homomorphic Encryption (HE) for gradient comparison [41, 28, 30, 32]. While these schemes are as accurate as their plain-text counterparts, they come with a substantial computational demand, which, given current computational demands, renders them unsuitable for real-world scenarios.

Another line of PPFL employs more lightweight cryptographic solutions, such as SA [35, 50], and relies on group testing instead of fine-grained individual-level information. Consequently, while they provide privacy by design, their accuracy is generally inferior to SoTA techniques.

Finally, client-level DP [36] could mitigate FR behaviour in a non-sybil setting, as it limits their effect via gradient clipping. On the other hand, such a defence is known to delay the model’s convergence, as it also injects noise into the training process. Consequently, while it could be appropriate against malicious attackers, applying DP to mitigate FR might have the same effect as FR in the first place.

II-B Privacy Attacks

One of the primary privacy concerns in FL is the exposure of the participant’s local data, which may include personal, sensitive, or proprietary information. Although FL provides privacy by design to some extent (as only the model updates are shared), many researchers have developed several attacks to show unintended information leakage [33]. Although there are a handful of privacy-preserving techniques, such as SA and DP, they usually have drawbacks, like decreasing the final accuracy of the model or preventing misbehaviour detection.

II-B1 Membership Inference Attack

ML models tend to exhibit different behaviours for members and non-members of the training dataset, often but not exclusively due to overfitting [52]. Since training data may include sensitive personal information (e.g., the medical conditions of hospital patients), learning such information via membership inference attack (MIA) [16] can be considered a privacy violation.

We can classify MIAs as black-box or white-box, depending on the access to the model parameters. It is well known that white-box does not provide any benefit compared to black-box [39]. However, this has been questioned recently [24].

The first MIA utilized shadow models [40] that mimic the behaviour of the target model. Since the membership information for these shadow models are known, an attack model can be trained on them to determine if a sample was used in the training of the target model. Later, other black-box attacks were introduced, which do not require training additional models. One such attack relies on the prediction loss [52] and uses a threshold to determine the presence or absence of a sample.

Recently, the authors of [25] observed that gradients of different instances are orthogonal in overparameterized models. They argued that this is due to the sparsity of the high-dimensional gradients, which behave similarly to independent random isotropic vectors. Based on this observation, they develop an attack based on cosine similarity, which can reveal membership if a target sample’s gradients are not orthogonal to the client’s update, which is the average of the training gradient samples. In this paper, we utilize the attacks by Yeom et al.  [52] and Li et al.  [25], referring to them as ℳYsuperscriptℳ𝑌\mathcal{M}^{Y}caligraphic_M start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_Y end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and ℳLsuperscriptℳ𝐿\mathcal{M}^{L}caligraphic_M start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT respectively. Both attacks are detailed in the Appendix.

II-B2 Property Inference Attack

PIA, instead of focusing on individual-level information, aims to infer sensitive properties of the entire local training datasets [1, 48]. Typically, it utilizes meta-classifiers trained on shadow-models [10, 34]; it simulates training on shadow datasets with and without the property in question and then trains a meta-classifier to differentiate between them.

Many attacks in the federated setting rely on gradient updates, such as those in [54, 43, 7], where the inferred property is the client’s label distributions. In this paper, we utilize the attacks by Wainakh et al. [43] and Dai. et al. [7], referring to them as 𝒫Wsuperscript𝒫𝑊\mathcal{P}^{W}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_W end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and 𝒫Dsuperscript𝒫𝐷\mathcal{P}^{D}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_D end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, respectively.

These attacks rely on the client’s gradients corresponding to the last layer, the model from the previous round, and the number of samples used by the client to infer the label distribution of the client’s training dataset. III Model

This section details how MIA and PIA can be used to address the FR problem. An overview of the entire scenario is shown in Fig. 2. In each round, the server broadcasts the previous aggregated model, which honest clients further train on their data, while FR clients apply one of the FR strategies. For MIA-based detection, the server shares a small dataset with the clients in each round, referred to as the canary set. In addition to local training, clients are required to train their local model on this canary set. The resulting model updates are sent back to the server, which, aside from aggregating them, implements one of the four proposed detection mechanisms, each involving different steps. MIA-based detection requires the server to train on the canary set 111Does not apply to ℳYsuperscriptℳ𝑌\mathcal{M}^{Y}caligraphic_M start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_Y end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT with client-side evaluation, which we will detail later in the paper. and compute the corresponding loss or cosine similarity metrics. In contrast, PIA requires training on auxiliary data (which can be generated from noise) to infer the underlying label distributions.

Assumptions

Similarly to the majority of the works focusing on privacy attacks (as shown in Sec. II), we rely on the standard assumption that the the server has access to some amount of training data (distinct from the clients). FR detection is performed by the server, and thus we also assume white-box access to the global model. Furthermore, as with most works addressing BTF and CE (also discussed in Sec. II), we do not utilize PPFL, meaning neither DP nor SA is enabled. After all, our goal is to demonstrate the suitability of using privacy attacks to detect FR clients. Additionally, following prior work, we assume that if a client is a free-rider, it remains a free-rider throughout all rounds.

In Tab. II, we compare the requirements for each FR detection mechanism we propose. These mechanisms cover a wide range of constrains for real-world scenarios, from requiring clients to train on external data to requiring the server to train on auxiliary data.

III-C FR detection via MIA

IV Experiments

In this section, we evaluate the performance of FRIDA under different experimental settings and compare it to feature-based FR detection techniques, which indirectly capture FR behaviour. Each Fig. represents a specific combination of model, dataset, number of clients, data distribution and free-riding strategy. By default, we examine AlexNet trained on CIFAR10, distributed across four clients (conducting three epochs of canary training in the case of MIA), where one client is FR using ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.

IV-A Set-up

Datasets & Models

We use CIFAR10 & CIFAR100 555Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images as standard image classification baseline datasets. These datasets comprise 60000 32x32 color images distributed across 10 and 100 classes, respectively. For the model architecture, we utilize AlexNet666ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks, a 62M parameters deep convolutional network composed of 5 convolutional layers and 2 fully connected layers. We also consider VGG-19, as shown in Table VI, which consists of 16 convolutional layers and 3 fully connected layers. For optimization, clients use the SGD optimizer 777Backpropagation and stochastic gradient descent method with momentum and weight decay. All experiments are repeated five times, so we present the empirical mean and standard deviation of our results.

FL & Simulation

The federated model is trained using FedAvg [31] as the aggregation rule. We focus on a cross-silo setting with N∈{4,8}𝑁48N\in\{4,8\}italic_N ∈ { 4 , 8 } clients with [0,1,2,4]0124[0,1,2,4][ 0 , 1 , 2 , 4 ] FR clients. We consider ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and ℱFsuperscriptℱ𝐹\mathcal{F}^{F}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as FR strategy. The FL set-up is simulated by assigning 4000 training samples to each client, drawn from IID and non-IID distributions. We use a Dirichlet distribution with parameter α=1.0𝛼1.0\alpha=1.0italic_α = 1.0 for the non-IID scenario to simulate minor heterogeneity and α=0.1𝛼0.1\alpha=0.1italic_α = 0.1 for more significant differences. Also, we allocate a representative portion of IID data to the server for the MIA-based detection. Baselines & Metrics

For feature-based outlier detection methods [57, 27], we compute the l2 norm and standard deviation of the client’s updates after each round 101010We also envisioned to compare our methods against DAGMM [27], we elaborate on this in the Appendix.. We then apply the z𝑧zitalic_z-score to flag outliers based on anomalous values, using the same threshold as for our detection mechanisms (i.e., 1111 standard deviation). This ensures a fair comparison between detection metrics, rather than comparing the anomaly detection mechanisms themselves. To evaluate the performance of the methods, we focus on precision, recall, and F1-score.

IV-B MIA Results

In our default experimental scenario, we assume that honest clients train over the canary set for three epochs, while a FR client does not train at all.

IV-B1 Loss-based detection

First, we evaluate the performance of Alg. 2 based on Yeom’s loss-based MIA. In Fig. 3(a), we show that the loss values of the canaries computed on the honest clients (blue, orange, green) and FR clients (red) are different. This difference becomes more pronounced as training progresses, as the impact of training over the canary set remains stable while the gradients for their training set continue to decrease due to convergence. This trend is also reflected in Fig. 6(a), where the F1-score improves across training rounds. While one canary epoch is sufficient to ensure a separation between honest and FR clients, more canary epochs further increase this separation. This helps improve the accuracy of the detection mechanism, as it becomes easier to define a threshold that separates both. In this regard, we examine the difference between client-side and server-side outlier detection in Ablation IV-E3.

IV-B2 Cosine-based detection

To verify the effectiveness of Algorithm 3, we show in Fig. 3(b) the difference between the cosine-similarity distribution of the gradients given members (canary samples) and non-members for FR and honest clients. A client is flagged as FR if the means of the two distributions are statistically indistinguishable, determined by a Student’s t𝑡titalic_t-test, indicating that the client has not trained over the canary subset. For honest clients (right), the slight difference between the two distributions is sufficient to infer membership. Similar to loss-based detection, the accuracy of this method improves as training progresses, particularly in later rounds. The F1-score metric is presented in Fig. 6(b).

IV-B3 Canary effect

MIA leverage the model’s tendency to overfit to the training dataset to infer membership [52]. This translates to our MIA-based detection mechanism, where greater overfitting to the canary dataset corresponds to improved FR detection performance. In Fig. 3(a), we observe that although FR clients are not training on the canary set, the canary loss is reduced in the early rounds. We argue that this results from improvements in the global model. However, after a certain number of rounds, the global model converges, and the canary loss is only reduced if the client has trained on the canary set.

We can induce overfitting by increasing the number of canary training epochs. In Table III, we examine the effect of the number of canary epochs on detection performance (averaged over 100 rounds). Note that more canary epochs impact the global model’s accuracy, as illustrated in Fig. 4. This presents a trade-off between global accuracy degradation and FR detection. On the other hand, FR have a more pronounced effect on global training that this canary-based detection mechanism, as visualized in Fig. 1.

IV-B4 Multi-round detection

We can improve the performance of the detection mechanism by combining knowledge from previous rounds. To achieve this, we implement a majority-voting scheme where a client is flagged as FR if it has been flagged as such more times than as honest within a given window of timesteps. Fig. 6(e) and Fig. 6(f) illustrate how this smooths and improves detection performance when combining knowledge from 10 consecutive rounds.

IV-C PIA Results

By default, we utilize 𝒫Wsuperscript𝒫𝑊\mathcal{P}^{W}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_W end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, but later we compare the FR detection based on both PIA methods.

IV-C1 Consistency-based detection

First, we verify our hypothesis that label distributions for FR clients differ from those of honest clients. In Fig. 5(a), we present how the inferred label distribution changes round-by-round for an honest (green) and FR client (red). As expected, there is a clear difference between both distributions. Also, for both FR attacks, the FR’s consistency score is generally lower than that of honest clients. This suggests that using an outlier detection method that considers this difference might be beneficial. The F1 score of the detection is shown in Fig. 6(c).

IV-C2 Diversity-based detection

Fig. 5(b) presents the diversity metric calculated for FR clients and honest clients. The results empirically confirm our hypothesis that the FR updates can be recreated more closely from the label distribution of the global model update and the uniform distribution than the updates of hones clients. As expected, the errors for honest clients (green) and FR clients (red) differ. The F1-score of the detection is shown in Fig. 6(d).

IV-C3 Utilized PIA

In Tab. V, we compare the detection performance of 𝒫Wsuperscript𝒫𝑊\mathcal{P}^{W}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_W end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and 𝒫Dsuperscript𝒫𝐷\mathcal{P}^{D}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_D end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT for the two FR strategies, as well as for consistency-based and diversity-based detection mechanisms. We found that while the 𝒫Wsuperscript𝒫𝑊\mathcal{P}^{W}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_W end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT-based FR detection generally outperforms the 𝒫Dsuperscript𝒫𝐷\mathcal{P}^{D}caligraphic_P start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_D end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT-based, it is not the case for consistency-based detection with ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as FR strategy. As our goal is not to study the nuanced differences between these attacks, we leave exploring the reason for this as future work.

IV-C4 Multi-round detection

Similarly to MIA-based detection, the performance of PIA-based FR detection improves when we aggregate knowledge across multiple rounds. Fig.  6(g) and Fig. 6(h) show the detection rates when decisions from 10 consecutive rounds are utilized.

IV-D State-of-the-Art Comparison

We compare our four proposed methods with two feature-based SoTA detection mechanisms in Tab. IV, where we extend the default setting with CIFAR-100 and 8 clients. FRIDA is outperformed by feature-based detection mechanisms in only 3 scenarios out of the 12, which demonstrates the effectiveness of directly inferring FR properties. Although we compared all detection mechanisms — both direct and indirect — separately in this work, they are complementary and can be combined for enhanced performance.

IV-E Ablation Study

Following our results for the default setup (AlexNet, CIFAR10, four clients, one FR using ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT), we study FR detection performance by systematically changing various aspects. We are also examine the fidelity of our methods, i.e., how it performs when there are no FR clients. The results are shown in Table VI.

IV-E1 Dataset

We evaluate the performance of the methods on a more complex dataset, such as CIFAR100, in Tab. IV and Tab. VI. We observe that most detection mechanisms showed improved performance in this scenario. We argue that this is primarily because the global model has not yet fully converged (see Fig. 7), making it more difficult for the FR update to blend into the honest clients’ updates. In the case of PIA, increasing the number of labels benefits detection performance, as the output of PIA contains more data points.

IV-E2 Client Number

Increasing the number of clients is beneficial for outlier detection methods, especially when only one FR client is present. As shown in Tab. IV and Tab. VI, most detection mechanisms show improved performance in the 8 client case. Specifically, in non-IID cases, we observed a notable increase in performance. Note that cosine-based detection relies on a student’s t𝑡titalic_t-test to differentiate the cosine similarity distribution between members and non-members for each client, which is why we do not observe an increase in performance for this detection mechanism.

IV-E3 Client-side vs server-side

In relation to loss-based FR detection, in Fig. 8 we compare client-side with server-side detection. In the latter, the server trains the global model on the canary set for two epochs (while the honest clients train for three). The threshold is determined using either the z𝑧zitalic_z-score method (standard deviation over the client’s canary losses) or based on the server’s loss on the canary set. We observe that client-side evaluation yields a similar False Positive Rate (FPR) to server-side evaluation when one FR client is present. However, in the absence of FR, the z𝑧zitalic_z-score method shows its limitations, resulting in a higher FPR. This underscores a broader limitation of the outlier detection techniques as FR detection: the lack of ground truth degrades the detection performance when there are no FR clients or too many. This issue is particularly critical in cross-silo scenarios, where a high FPR can affect the participant’s trust in the learning process. In this work, we adhere with the z𝑧zitalic_z-score mechanism for loss-based detection (i.e., client-side evaluation) to compare various direct and indirect metrics under the same experimental setting.

IV-E4 FR Ratio

Although in this work, we aim to provide a fair comparison among detection methods, where we primarily consider a single FR client, a critical aspect of FR detection is how these methods perform when multiple FR clients are present. Tab. VI presents the results for 8 clients with 2 and 4 FR clients. As the number of FR clients increases, all anomaly-based FR detection methods are affected due to the inherent limitations of lacking a ground truth. However, for 50%percent5050\%50 % of FR, feature-based metrics have a poor F1-score while FRIDA succeeds, demonstrating improved robustness when directly inferring FR properties.

IV-E5 FR Strategy

Most detection methods have a higher performance when FR clients use ℱFsuperscriptℱ𝐹\mathcal{F}^{F}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT (e.g., PIA and feature-based detection methods have perfect F1-scores in CIFAR-100, see Tab. VII in the Appendix), which is commonly used as a baseline in previous works. However, we observe a general decrease in detection performance when FR client relies on ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT (also for feature-based metrics), which lead us to believe that it improves stealth. Consequently, we selected that as default111111While Tab. IV corresponds to ℱLsuperscriptℱ𝐿\mathcal{F}^{L}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, in the top part of Tab. VI we show the results for ℱFsuperscriptℱ𝐹\mathcal{F}^{F}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.; this strategy adds Gaussian noise to the last global gradient instead of the last global model as ℱFsuperscriptℱ𝐹\mathcal{F}^{F}caligraphic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.

We vary the noise multiplier α𝛼\alphaitalic_α and the noise power γ𝛾\gammaitalic_γ, which is the exponent applied to the iteration number (see Eq. 14 in the Appendix). These parameters affect the standard deviation of the Gaussian distribution 𝒩⁢(Gt−1,α⋅σ⋅tγ)𝒩superscript𝐺𝑡1⋅𝛼𝜎superscript𝑡𝛾\mathcal{N}(G^{t-1},\alpha\cdot\sigma\cdot t^{\gamma})caligraphic_N ( italic_G start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_t - 1 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , italic_α ⋅ italic_σ ⋅ italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_γ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) from which the FR client draws the noise. IV-F Discussion

FRIDA, the proposed solution, is outperformed by state-of-the-art methods in a few cases, primarily when there are a large number of clients and few free-riders. This indicates that inference-based detection enhances robustness in edge scenarios with either few clients, a high number of free-riders, or diverse data distributions. By comparing direct and indirect metrics using the same detection mechanism, we experimentally demonstrate the suitability of directly inferring information for free-rider detection, paving the way for a new family of detection methods.

IV-F1 MIA

We experimentally observed that MIA performs well in IID scenarios but struggles with canary optimization in non-IID settings. In scenarios with either no or many FR clients, the cosine-based detection is especially advantageous as it does not require an additional outlier detection mechanism. Instead, it identifies a client as FR based solely on its own properties, without considering the behavior of others.

IV-F2 PIA

Our results indicated that PIA is particularly effective in scenarios with a large number of labels, as more labels provide PIA with more granular information about the clients. Moreover, in case of high dataset diversity, both approaches outperformed the SoTA mechanisms, with diversity-based methods outperforming consistency-based ones in non-IID settings, and vice versa in IID settings.

V Conclusion

In this work, we introduced FRIDA (free-rider detection using privacy attacks), a framework leveraging inference attacks to detect free-riders. We present a new family of detection methods that highlight new synergies between privacy (via inference attacks) and security (via free-riding detection) within Federated Learning. Specifically, we proposed four detection mechanisms based on membership and property inference attacks, each designed to directly infer information from the underlying datasets. We demonstrated the robustness of FRIDA across various scenarios, often outperforming traditional mechanisms that focus on indirect free-riding effects.

Limitations & Future Works

We used z𝑧zitalic_z-score across all detection methods, which has inherent limitations, particularly in scenarios with either no free-riders or many free-riders. Additionally, MIA-based detection methods might degrade global model performance.121212This could be improved, as shown in Fig. 3(a), where a single canary epoch is sufficient to separate honest and FR clients. Another limitation is the focus on Computer Vision; we envision to extend our work to Natural Language in the future. We also left the study of various privacy-preserving techniques as future work, as they inherently affect the performance of the utilized MIA & PIA.

The paper also lacks a study of the trade-off between exploration and exploitation; that is, we did not study what is the optimal round for removing the detected clients and how does that affect the global model’s performance. Finally, all proposed detection mechanisms are independent, so combining them could result in superior detection performance, which we also intend to explore in the future.

-A Free-riding Attacks

-A1 FR by Fraboni et. al.

[8] introduced a theoretical framework that formalizes free-rider attacks in federated learning schemes based on model averaging, relying on modelling SGD as a continuous time process. This framework provides theoretical guarantees on the convergence of the aggregated model to the optimal solution, which is critical for the attacker not to interfere with the learning process. -B Membership Inference Attacks

-B1 Yeom et. al.

[52] characterizes the effect of overfitting on membership advantage, which is defined as how well an adversary can distinguish whether x∼Ssimilar-to𝑥𝑆x\sim Sitalic_x ∼ italic_S or x∼Dsimilar-to𝑥𝐷x\sim Ditalic_x ∼ italic_D, where S𝑆Sitalic_S is the training set and D𝐷Ditalic_D the distribution from which the training set was drawn. They found a clear dependence of membership advantage on generalization error, leading them to propose a straightforward attack, which we call the Yeom attack and noted as ℳYsuperscriptℳ𝑌\mathcal{M}^{Y}caligraphic_M start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_Y end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. This attack is based on the prediction loss of a target sample s𝑠sitalic_s. The attacker infers membership if ℒ⁢(s,θ)ℒ𝑠𝜃\mathcal{L}(s,\theta)caligraphic_L ( italic_s , italic_θ ) is lower than the expected training loss, given a subset of training samples that are part of the attacker’s knowledge.

-C2 Dai et. al.

[7] is made up of three steps. First, the null classes (i.e., the labels that were not used during training) are removed. This is done by examining the gradient changes; the labels with no positive gradients are considered null classes. Then, the label basis (i.e., the gradient changes after training with a single type of label) and the unified base (i.e., the effect of training with the same amount of labels from all non-null classes) are extracted. This is done by simulating training for each of these scenarios using D~~𝐷\tilde{D}over~ start_ARG italic_D end_ARG. Finally, the label distribution for non-null classes is acquired using by checking which linear combination of the basis (with non-negative coefficients) is the best to reproduce the gradients of the client.

-D DAGMM

We wanted to compare our mechanisms to DAGMM [27] as the SoTA FR detection mechanism. However, it relies on the parameters of the target model, which results in a substantial computational bottleneck even for medium-sized networks such as AlexNet. Therefore, and since previous DAGMM works do not give details of the architecture, we restricted its use to the last layer of the client’s update as the input to the autoencoder. Specifically, we used the autoencoder with three layers consisting of [100,10,1]100101[100,10,1][ 100 , 10 , 1 ] neurons, with the decoder mirroring the encoder. The GMM consists of three layers with [8,4,2]842[8,4,2][ 8 , 4 , 2 ] neurons, where the last layer specifies the number of mixture components. We train the DAGMM for 100100100100 epochs with a batch size of 16161616. Despite our efforts, this was proved to be ineffective. Consequently, we only compare FRIDA to feature-based outlier detection methods.

-E Orthogonality-based FR Detection

Based on our empirical results, we suggest another FR detection mechanism inspired by the cosine-based MIA ℳLsuperscriptℳ𝐿\mathcal{M}^{L}caligraphic_M start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. However, unlike MIA-based solutions, it does not require clients to be trained in external data. Instead, it leverages FR clients’ distinct cosine similarity distributions: we empirically observed that with free-riders implementing Fℱsuperscript𝐹ℱF^{\mathcal{F}}italic_F start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT caligraphic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT strategy, the mean and standard deviation of the cosine similarity distributions are orders of magnitude smaller than those of honest clients. Based on this finding, we improve cosine-based detection by setting a threshold to the standard deviation of the cosine similarity distribution, flagging a client as a free-rider if it falls below this threshold.
